{"v":"1.0.0","d":{"name":"Effect.Ref","comments":[{"tag":"LineComment","_1":" | This module defines the `Ref` type for mutable value references, as well"},{"tag":"LineComment","_1":" | as actions for working with them."},{"tag":"LineComment","_1":" |"},{"tag":"LineComment","_1":" | You'll notice that all of the functions that operate on a `Ref` (e.g."},{"tag":"LineComment","_1":" | `new`, `read`, `write`) return their result wrapped in an `Effect`."},{"tag":"LineComment","_1":" | Working with mutable references is considered effectful in PureScript"},{"tag":"LineComment","_1":" | because of the principle of purity: functions should not have side"},{"tag":"LineComment","_1":" | effects, and should return the same result when called with the same"},{"tag":"LineComment","_1":" | arguments. If a `Ref` could be written to without using `Effect`, that"},{"tag":"LineComment","_1":" | would cause a side effect (the effect of changing the result of subsequent"},{"tag":"LineComment","_1":" | reads for that `Ref`). If there were a function for reading the current"},{"tag":"LineComment","_1":" | value of a `Ref` without the result being wrapped in `Effect`, the result"},{"tag":"LineComment","_1":" | of calling that function would change each time a new value was written to"},{"tag":"LineComment","_1":" | the `Ref`. Even creating a new `Ref` is effectful: if there were a"},{"tag":"LineComment","_1":" | function for creating a new `Ref` with the type `forall s. s -> Ref s`,"},{"tag":"LineComment","_1":" | then calling that function twice with the same argument would not give the"},{"tag":"LineComment","_1":" | same result in each case, since you'd end up with two distinct references"},{"tag":"LineComment","_1":" | which could be updated independently of each other."},{"tag":"LineComment","_1":" |"},{"tag":"LineComment","_1":" | _Note_: `Control.Monad.ST` provides a pure alternative to `Ref` when"},{"tag":"LineComment","_1":" | mutation is restricted to a local scope."}],"imports"